The author crammed way too many characters and subplots into this sequel, which left everything feeling 2-dimensional. And the main plot/resolution was disappointing in its naivete. Significant moral and ethical issues lurking in the background, resolved with all the wisdom and subtlety of a 10-year old.

Title: Ring of Bright Water (Ring of Bright Water, #1)
Author: Gavin Maxwell
My Review:
An enjoyable read overall. I hadn't heard of this before, and picked it up on one of my "random book" sprees before Coronavirus shut the library down. The author has a great sense of humor and the narrative is engaging.

There are a number of interesting details that warranted further research- so it took a lot longer to read than I anticipated. For example, the author was involved early on in a basking shark fishery- a regrettable enterprise in many ways.

https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-highlands-islands-21064835

There's also a casual mention of taking 150 ducks in one day hunting...! I'm inclined to continue the trilogy (didn't realize as I was reading this that there are two more volumes).

“We are not Navajo, however; we are not Inuit people or Sioux. We are contemporary citizens living in a technological world. Title: Ayn Rand and the World She Made
Author: Anne C. Heller
My Review:
This is an interesting biography, but not historical as I expected. There are a number of anecdotes related from various sources, but they are not always well supported or integrated, and there is a lot of speculation. For example, the author speculates about Rand's psychological makeup without really delving into much detail. She relates some anecdotes about Rand's mother and her "sometimes tyrannical" presence at home, without giving a clear impression of what this means. I was confused about whether Rand's home life was oppressive or she was just an extremely arrogant individual (I suspect more of the latter than the former, given how she treated those around her).

The author makes a lot of excuses for her as well. For instance, Rand made a point of stating that "deception" had no place in the life of her idealized "rational egoist," but then throughout her own life was responsible for some pretty extreme acts of deceit. The author excuses most of this by appealing to the hardships she had to endure, which while legitimately difficult hardly answer the objection on any rational grounds. It seems to me that Rand is her own worst enemy, and while her philosophy has appealing features it fails in practice because it does not account for the complexity of human nature.

Ayn Rand was an interesting person, a fantastic and prolific writer, but a little too full of herself and her mythos. She surrounded herself with worshipers, and had no time for critics. That came across well in the book- I suspect the author is more of a worshiper than a semi-objective biographer. I could think of better ways to spend my time, however... I won't be re-reading this one.
